1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 d6 3. e4 $5 {An interesting choice to steer the game into an
e4 e5 type of structure, using the fact that, compared to the classical e4-e5
line, Black's bishop remains behind the pawn chain due to 2...d6} Nc6 (3... c5
{Black doesn't let us to play for d2-d4} 4. f4 $1 {But we will go for the
other break!} Nc6 (4... exf4 $6 {This is a very rare case when engine likes
for White the King's gambit!} 5. Qf3 Qh4+ 6. g3 $1 fxg3 7. hxg3 $16 {White has
a huge lead in development}) 5. Nc3 $1 exf4 6. Qf3 Nd4 (6... Qh4+ 7. g3 fxg3 8.
hxg3 Qf6 9. Qg2 $5 $16 {huge lead in development}) 7. Bb5+ $1 Bd7 (7... Nxb5 8.
Nxb5 $36) 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qd3 Ne7 (9... Qg4 $2 {concrete but bad} 10. Nd5 $1
Qxg2 11. O-O-O Qxh1 12. Bxd4 cxd4 13. Nc7+ Kd8 14. Nxa8 $18) 10. O-O-O Nec6 11.
Nd5 Be7 12. Nf3 $16) (3... Nf6 4. Nc3 g6 5. d4 Nc6 (5... exd4 {[%cal Gd1d4]} 6.
Qxd4 Bg7 7. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gd4d2,Gf2f3,Gg2g4] Typical position, Whites play
is very natural.}) (5... Qe7 {most reliable move} 6. a4 $1 {Very deep, with
the point of having Ba3 resource.} Bg7 7. dxe5 Qxe5 (7... dxe5 $2 8. Ba3 Qd7 9.
Qc1 $16) 8. Bd3 O-O {[%csl Gd1]} 9. Qd2 Nc6 10. Nge2 Be6 11. O-O-O $14 {
White position still remains easier to play.}) 6. dxe5 {going for the Philidor
type endgame makes perfect sense, as Black wasted the ...g6 move, as he will
need the bishop on d6.} dxe5 (6... Nxe5 7. f4 $16 {is just horrible for Black.}
) 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 (7... Nxd8 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Nb5 Nc6 10. Nxd6+ cxd6 11. Nd2 $14 {
[%cal Gf2f3,Ge1c1] White definitely enjoys such a pleasant endgame.}) 8. O-O-O+
Bd6 9. g3 Be6 10. Bg2 $14 {f4 next with pleasant advantage}) (3... f5 4. d4 $1
fxe4 (4... exd4 5. Qxd4 Nf6 (5... Qf6 $5 {An interesting choice to try and
steer the game towards an endgame; Black wants to argue that the structure
that is now on the board favours him.} 6. Nf3 {This double-edged move is
interesting.} (6. Qa4+ {This forced move doesn't achieve that much for White.}
Bd7 7. Bxf6 Bxa4 8. Bb2 Bd7 9. Nc3 fxe4 10. Nxe4 d5 11. Nc3 c6 12. O-O-O Nf6
13. Re1+ Kd8 14. Nf3 $14 {Maybe White can still retain a nominal plus thanks
to the weakened dark squares in the position, although black play is kind of
easy.}) 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 Qxd4 (7... Bd7 8. Bxc6 $1 {Concrete idea} Bxc6 9. e5 $1
dxe5 10. Nxe5 Rd8 11. Qf4 Ne7 (11... Bxg2 {Very risky business} 12. Rg1 Be4 13.
Nd2 Qh6 $1 {Only move} (13... Bxc2 $4 14. Rc1 Be4 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Qxe4 $18 {
Black is completely lost, with Rc7 coming next.}) 14. Qxh6 Nxh6 15. O-O-O Nf7
16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17. Nxe4 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 fxe4 19. Rd7+ Ke6 {[%cal Gd7d8,Gd7c7]
And white has 2 choices, both are fine, after which Black will need a miracle
to survive.}) 12. Nd2 Ng6 13. Qe3 f4 14. Qe2 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Qe6 16. Bxc7 Qxe2+
17. Kxe2 Rd7 18. Bxf4 Bxg2 19. Rhg1 Bc6 20. Nc4 $14 {Black definitely has
compensation, but we cannot be unhappy about the fact that we are a pawn up.})
8. Nxd4 fxe4 9. Nxc6 a6 10. Nd4+ axb5 11. Nxb5 Kd7 12. c4 $36 {[%csl Ye4][%cal
Ge1h1,Gb1d2,Gb5c3] I like this endgame a bit more, because besides the monster
on b2 we can hope to create counterplay against the somewhat vulnerable pawn
on e4. The pair of bishops is not that relevant, as its pretty tough to find a
good home for the c8 bishop.}) 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... fxe4 7. O-O-O {it is very
similar to what we have seen after the 4...fxe4, all the ideas remain valid.})
7. Qe3 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O {Punzón Moraleda, Jesús - Parkkinen, Jyrki, 1-0,
WC32/sf03, 2008, https://lichess.org/4tkI2LfE} 9. Kb1 $5 {There was nothing
wrong with exf5, but playing in gambit style seems more fitting and coherent
with what we previously analyzed.} Nxe4 (9... fxe4 10. f3 {with a direct
transposition.}) 10. Nd5 $1 {Very instructive move, we don't go for material,
but we go instead for the dark square bishop; this way, the monster on b2 will
be a reigning king over the a1-h8 diagonal forever.} Be6 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. Nh3
Rae8 13. f3 Nf6 14. Qf2 $14 {[%cal Gh3f4,Gf1d3,Gh1e1,Gf1b5] 14.Bb5 was another
possible move; the different color bishop middlegame was also favorable for
white, but even after a slow retreating move, white retains a pleasant plus
and more than enough compensation.}) 5. Nc3 $1 {We continue to focus on
developing our pieces, and we use the fact that the pawn is still on d4 to
meet ...Nc6 effectively.} (5. dxe5 $6 {Most natural move is met by the
energetic response:} Nc6 $1 6. exd6 Nf6 $1 7. dxc7 Bb4+ $1 8. c3 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1
Ba5 $15 {And despite being a pawn up, Blacks development advantage will crash
through Whites position.}) 5... Nc6 (5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Nf6 7. O-O-O {There is
no need to rush taking on e4. it is very similar to what we have seen after
the 4...fxe4, all the ideas remain valid.} Nc6 8. Qe3 Qe7 (8... Be7 9. f3 $5 {
Interesting idea, as we are more than happy if Black opens up more lines.} O-O
10. Kb1 {Prophylaxis against ...Bg5 ideas.} exf3 11. Nxf3 $36 {[%cal Gf1c4,
Gh2h3,Gg2g4] With a strong initiative, as the extra Black pawn on d6 is not
going anywhere, and White has good attacking prospects.}) 9. Nge2 Bd7 {Black
does best to try and castle long.} 10. Nf4 O-O-O 11. h3 Kb8 12. g4 $1 $14 {
[%cal Gc1b1,Gg4g5,Gc3d5,Gf1g2,Gf1c4] And here even if Blacks king is safer,
White retains a pleasant initiative, as it is yet unclear how to develop the
rest of Blacks pieces, while in a couple of moves white achieves perfect
coordination.}) (5... Qe7 6. Nge2 Nf6 7. Qd2 {As usual, we don't really care
about the material, so developing the pieces is far more important.} g6 (7...
Nc6 8. d5 Nb8 9. Ng3 g6 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Ngxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. Nxe4 $14
{With a nice positional edge.}) 8. O-O-O Bg7 9. dxe5 dxe5 (9... Qxe5 $2 10. Nd5
$1 {We transition into a more or less winning endgame.} Qxd5 11. Qxd5 Nxd5 12.
Bxg7 Rg8 13. Bb2 Ne7 14. Nc3 Bf5 15. Rg1 $5 {One of the many options available.
The pawn on e4 cannot survive for long.} g5 16. g4 Bg6 17. Bg2 $16 {Close to
lost endgame for Black.}) 10. Nb5 $1 {Very concrete idea, to use the awkward
queen on c7.} O-O 11. Ba3 c5 12. Nec3 $16 {I just dont see Black surviving
such an onslaught, Bc4 and Qd6 are possible ideas, and the questions are
almost impossible to respond to.}) 6. d5 Nce7 (6... Nd4 $6 {An active square,
but that knight is more of a source of play for White.} 7. Nxe4 Nf6 (7... Bf5
8. Bd3 Nf6 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. Bxd4 exd4 11. Ne2 $16 {White dominates the light
squares and also the pawn on d4 will be collected.}) 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Bxd4 exd4
10. Bb5+ $14 {Black has to make a king move, so he will play the rest of the
game with the king in the center, and also the d4 pawn will sooner than later
be collected.}) (6... Nb8 7. Nxe4 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Bd3 Be7 10. Ne2 $14 {
With a strategical battle ahead, but at least White safely secures the e4
square for the rest of the game with a nice edge.}) 7. Nxe4 Bf5 8. Qf3 $5 {
A clever way to defend the hanging knight} Nf6 (8... Qd7 9. c4 Nf6 10. Nxf6+
gxf6 11. Ne2 $14 {With Ng3 coming next, Whites position is for choice.}) 9.
Bb5+ $1 {Very annoying move to disrupt any kind of coordination in Blacks camp.
} Kf7 (9... c6 $4 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6+ Nxc6 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 13. Qxf5 $18) (
9... Bd7 $2 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 (10... Nxd7 11. c4 $16 {Whites active queen of f3
does a tremendous job to stop anyway for Black to untangle the position.}) 11.
Qxf6 $1 {Very easy tactics.} gxf6 12. Nxf6+ Kd8 13. Nxd7 Kxd7 14. Rd1 $16 {
[%cal Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gf2f4] And converting the pawn advantage into a win is
purely a matter of technique.}) 10. Nh3 $1 {Sharp move, leaving Black with the
choice to force the matters or continue to weaken his kingside with ...h6.}
Nxe4 (10... h6 11. Nxf6 gxf6 12. O-O-O $16 {Now white has a main strategic
objective to achieve: trade the light squares bishop in the near future with
Bd3, after which all the holes on the kingside become more vulnerable.}) 11.
Bd3 $1 {We were relying on this double pin, which allows us to safely
recapture a piece either or on e4 or f5.} Nc5 12. Bxf5 Nxf5 13. Qxf5+ Qf6 14.
Qh5+ Qg6 15. Qxg6+ Kxg6 16. O-O-O $14 {Black successfully entered an endgame,
but this doesn't mean his troubles ended. f4 next, or Rhe1-f4 leaves Black in
an extremely uncomfortable situation as his king on g6 is more of an issue
than a strength.}) 4. Bb5 Bd7 5. Nf3 {we have reached a Ruy Lopez Stainitz
defence, where we have already b3-Bb2 on the board} Nf6 (5... g5 $5 6. h3 Bg7
7. d4 Nxd4 {[%cal Gb5d7]} (7... exd4 8. Bxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gb2d4]} 9. Bxd4 (9.
Nxd4) 9... Nf6 10. Qd3 $1 $14 {Nbd2-0-0-0 next}) 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Nxd4 exd4 10.
Bxd4 Be5 11. Na3 O-O-O 12. Bxe5 dxe5 13. Qxd7+ Rxd7 14. Nc4 $14 {The endgame
is clearly in whites favour due to the strange kingside structure.}) 6. Nc3 g6
(6... a6 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Qe2 g6 9. d4 Qe7 10. a4 $1 {the typical motif} Bg7 11.
dxe5 dxe5 12. Ba3 Qe6 13. O-O $14) 7. d4 $1 exd4 8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. Nxc6 bxc6 (9...
Bxc6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qd3 $16 {Makes whites life even simpler.}) 10. Bd3 O-O
11. Qd2 d5 12. O-O-O Re8 (12... Qe7 13. h4 $5 d4 14. Ne2 c5 15. f3 a5 16. h5 a4
17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Nf4 axb3 19. axb3 $14 {[%cal Gd7e6,Gf4e6,Gd3c4] The game is
double-edged, but White seems to be in time to consolidate his position-}) 13.
Rhe1 $14 {White coordination is very good and has good prospects to go on and
achieve a very big advantage.} *

