1. b3 b6 2. e4 $1 Bb7 {is the most logical move, but let's check for fun what
happens if Black is playing e5, the Sicilian, the French, the Scandinavian, or
the Caro-Kann with b3-b6 included! :)} (2... c6 {the Caro Kann is not so great
here} 3. d4 d5 4. e5 Bf5 (4... c5 5. dxc5 $1 bxc5 6. c4 $1 $16) 5. Be2 e6 6.
Nf3 $16 {This is an improved Caro Kann for White. First of all here Black
doesn't have the Qb6 lines, and in general, b3 can be useful for White to play
with c2-c4}) (2... e6 {also the French is not great for Black when b3-b6 are
included} 3. Bb2 d5 4. exd5 $1 exd5 5. Nf3 Bb7 6. a4 $5 Nf6 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8. Bxf6
gxf6 9. Nc3 $14) (2... e5 3. Nf3 {very interesting to note that when b3-b6 are
included a lot of lines of the Petroff or the Italian are not playable for
Black!} Nc6 (3... Nf6 4. Nxe5 d6 $4 (4... Nxe4 $4 5. Qf3 $18) (4... Bb7 5. Bc4
Qe7 6. d4 d6 7. Ba3 Nbd7 8. f4 O-O-O 9. O-O Nxe5 10. fxe5 Nxe4 $16) 5. Bb5+ $18
{big difference comparing to the Petroff!}) 4. Bc4 $16 {White is already better
} Bc5 (4... Nf6 5. Ng5 d5 6. exd5 Na5 7. O-O $16) 5. c3 Nf6 6. d4 exd4 7. e5 d5
8. Bb5 $18 {thanks to the inclusion of b7-b6, now the Max Lange variation is
just winning for White}) (2... d5 {actually the Scandinavian may be the best
choice for Black when b3-b6 are included} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3 $1 ({now would
be wrong for White to play the normal} 4. Nc3 Qe6+ $1 5. Be2 Bb7 $11 6. Nf3
Bxf3 $1 7. gxf3 Nc6 $11) 4... Bb7 5. d4 e6 6. Bc4 Qd8 7. Qe2 Nf6 8. Bb2 Bd6 9.
Nc3 O-O 10. O-O-O $5 $36 {White has ideas like Ne5-d5, or can start by taking
space on the kingside with h4-h5}) (2... c5 {if Black wants to play in the
Sicilian style, then he should start with 2...c5, as after 3.Bb2 his best is
Nc6! without allowing White to play d4-cxd4-Qxd4} 3. Bb2 Nc6 {Black stops d2-d4
} (3... Bb7 4. d4 $3 {a key move that almost refutes Black's system} (4. Nc3
Nc6 {unfortunately gets in the way of our main idea.}) 4... cxd4 (4... Bxe4 $2
5. d5 e6 6. Nc3 {White is too much ahead in development} exd5 (6... Bg6 7. h4
$1 h5 8. Nf3 $18) 7. f3 Bg6 8. Nxd5 Ne7 9. Nh3 $5 $16) 5. Qxd4 Nc6 (5... a6 6.
Nc3 d6 7. O-O-O e5 8. Qd2 Nf6 9. f4 Nbd7 10. Nf3 Rc8 11. Bc4 b5 12. Bd5 Qc7 13.
Bxb7 Qxb7 14. Rhe1 Be7 15. fxe5 dxe5 {1-0 Raahul,V (2344)-Dizdarevic,E (2423)
Arandjelovac ASK-1 GM 2021 (2)} 16. Nd5 $1 $18) 6. Qd2 Nf6 7. Nc3 e6 8. O-O-O
Bb4 9. f3 Qe7 (9... d5 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 O-O 12. exd5 exd5 13. Ne2 Rc8 14.
Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 $16 {1-0 Daneshvar,B (2490)-Santos Ruiz,M (2581) Titled
Tuesday intern op 30th Aug Early Chess.com INT blitz 2022 (11)}) 10. Kb1 O-O
11. Nge2 Rfd8 12. Qc1 $1 {unpinning Nc3} d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Rxd5 15.
Rxd5 exd5 16. Ng3 $16) 4. Nf3 Bb7 5. Nc3 e6 (5... Nd4 6. Bd3 $5 {defending the
e4 pawn, and preparing Nxd4-cxd4-Ne2} Nf6 7. O-O e6 8. Re1 Be7 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10.
Na4 $5 e5 11. c3 dxc3 12. Bxc3 d6 (12... Qb8 13. Nb2 O-O 14. Nc4 d6 15. Ne3 $14
{Qf3-Nf5 next}) 13. Bb5+ $5 (13. Bb2 O-O 14. Nc3 $14 {also possible}) 13... Kf8
14. d4 Nxe4 15. Bb2 $36 {with a huge initiative}) 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8.
Nxc6 $5 Bxc6 9. Bd3 {Thanks to Bb2 White has an interesting version of the
Open Sicilian} Bb4 10. Qf3 Rc8 11. O-O Qc7 12. Ne2 $36 (12. Ba6 $5 Rd8 13. Nb5
Bxb5 14. Bxb5 Qxc2 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qxf6 Bc3 17. Rac1 Bxf6 18. Rxc2 $14)) 3.
Nc3 e6 (3... g6 4. Bb2 Bg7 5. d4 e6 6. Nf3 Ne7 {This was reached in my game
against the German player Seel, and now White would have been much better after
} 7. h4 $1 h5 8. Qe2 $16 {000 next}) 4. Bb2 Nf6 (4... c5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6
7. Qd2 {transposes in 2...c5}) (4... d5 5. exd5 exd5 6. Qe2+ $1 $16 {similiar
to 2...e6 that we have checked before}) 5. e5 Nd5 (5... Ne4 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. h4
$1 {White wants to take space on the kingside with h4-h5} c5 (7... d6 8. Qe2
Bb7 9. Nf3 $14) (7... h5 8. Nf3 Be7 9. d3 Bb7 10. d4 $14) 8. Qg4 Bb7 9. h5 {
White is already better} Nc6 10. O-O-O a6 11. Nf3 h6 12. Kb1 b5 13. d4 cxd4 {
this was reached in the game Nihal-Andreikin at the 2021 World Cup, and now I
suggest} 14. Bd3 $5 $16 {with the idea Be4 and only then White takes back on
d4. According to engines, White is already close to winning}) 6. Nxd5 Bxd5 7.
h4 $1 {same idea as after 5...Ne4} c5 (7... d6 8. f4 $1 Be7 (8... dxe5 9. fxe5
{Followed by Qg4, long castling with advantage.}) 9. Qg4 {This is clearly
better for White as it not so easy to defend g7.}) 8. Qg4 h5 {was reached in
the Adhiban-Salgado 2022} 9. Qf4 $1 $146 (9. Qg3 $6 Nc6 $1 $13) 9... d6 (9...
Nc6 $4 {not possible after Qf4} 10. c4 $18 {where Balck doesn't have Be4}) (
9... g6 10. Nh3 Bh6 11. Ng5 $16) 10. Nf3 $14 *

