1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 {Black's two main moves are 3...Nf6 and 3...d5. In
this chapter we will check the sidelines, namely 3...d6, 3...a6 and especially
the move 3...g6} g6 (3... d6 4. Nf3 {now Black should decide if he wants to
develop with Nf6 or with f5-Nf6} Nf6 (4... f5 $6 5. d4 $1 {as a rule, when
Black plays with f5, we can break immediately with d4!} e4 6. d5 $1 exf3 (6...
Nce7 7. Nd4 Nf6 8. c4 Ng6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Qc2 $16 {White will continue with 000,
with a better position}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 (7... fxg2 $4 8. Bxg2 $18) 8. gxf3 $16 {
we have a better dark squares bishop and the f5 pawn is clearly misplaced}) 5.
d4 $5 {usually we don't break with d2-d4 when Black hasn't played f5, but here
we'll make an exception} e4 (5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9.
O-O-O Be6 10. Rg1 $1 $16 {White will continue with g2-g4}) 6. d5 $1 Nb4 $1 (
6... exf3 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Qxf3 $14) 7. Ng5 $1 h6 8. a3 Nxc2+ (8... Nbxd5 9.
Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxd5 Nf6 11. Qd2 $14) 9. Qxc2 hxg5 10. Bb5+ $1 Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7
12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Qxe4+ Be7 14. Nc3 {engine shows his classical zeros, but
from a human point of view it looks more pleasant to play with White}) (3... a6
{this move is against Bb5} 4. c4 Nf6 (4... d5 $5 {this is an engine-style move}
5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nc3 Qd6 7. Nf3 Bf5 8. a3 $1 {against Nb4 ideas} Nf6 9. b4 e4 $1
(9... Be7 10. b5 $1 $14) 10. Qc2 $5 Rd8 11. Rd1 $36) 5. Nf3 {but comparing to
the line 1.b3 e5 2.Bb2 Nc6 3.e3 Nf6 4.Nf3, which we will check in a few
chapters, includes the moves a6 and c4 is clearly in White's favour}) 4. Nf3 (
4. f4 {would be in true Larsen spirit, but unfortunately modern engines are
showing a concrete solution for Black} Bg7 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bb5 Nge7 $1 7. fxe5 O-O
$1 {and Black is completely fine}) 4... Bg7 5. c4 (5. d4 e4 $1 6. Nfd2 f5 {
and Black has a good game}) 5... d6 {consolidating the e5 pawn} (5... Nge7 {
allows a nice idea} 6. b4 $1 Nxb4 $1 {Black should go for a concrete play} (
6... d6 7. b5 Nb8 8. d4 O-O {happened in Karjakin-Kramnik blitz 2019} 9. dxe5
$1 Nd7 10. Be2 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bxe5 dxe5 13. Qb3 $14 {White has some
extra space on the queenside, and a more pleasant position}) 7. Bxe5 Bxe5 8.
Nxe5 {White has an extra central pawn. The only way for Black to justify this
is to play something fast} O-O 9. a3 $1 Nbc6 10. Nxc6 dxc6 $1 {playing for a
very fast development} (10... Nxc6 11. Nc3 $14) 11. Nc3 (11. d4 c5 $1 12. dxc5
Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 Bf5 $44) 11... c5 $1 {against d2-d4} (11... Bf5 {allows} 12. d4
c5 13. dxc5 $14 {comparing to 11.d4, here if Black exchanges queens White can
take back with the rook. It's true that our pawn structure on the queenside is
not great, but still we have an extra pawn and Black should be the one proving
compensation here}) 12. Be2 b6 {and Here I like the following plan:} 13. h4 $5
(13. O-O Bb7 14. Bf3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxd2 16. Ne4 $44) 13... Bb7 14. Bf3 Bxf3 15.
Qxf3 {White wants to continue with h5} Qd3 $1 16. Qe2 {the position is unclear,
but from the practical point of view it should be more fun to play White here})
(5... f5 6. d4 e4 7. Ng1 $1 Nce7 8. Nc3 Nf6 {Shimanov-Niemann 2021} 9. d5 O-O
10. Nge2 $16) 6. Nc3 {now Black should decide if he wants to play with Nge7,
with Nf6 or with f5+Nf6} Nge7 (6... f5 7. d4 $1 {only against f5 we will break
immediately with d4!} e4 8. Ng1 $1 {the knight belongs to the e2 square} Nf6 9.
Nge2 O-O 10. h4 $1 $14 {ensuring the f4 square. We can then continue with
Nf4-Qd2-000 with a very interesting position, where it should be unpleasant to
play Black}) (6... Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O e4 $5 (8... Re8 9. d3 h6 10. a3 $14 {
White can continue with useful moves like Re1-Bf1 with a fighting but slightly
better position}) 9. Ne1 Re8 10. d3 Bf5 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. dxe4
Bxe4 14. Bf3 $14 {we have the typical slighly better structure}) 7. Be2 O-O 8.
O-O h6 9. Rc1 Be6 10. d3 $14 {we have reached an interesting middlegame
position, where we can continue with moves like Re1-Bf1-Rc2-Qa1. We are
slightly better, but of course, all the fight is ahead} *

