{[%evp 0,33,18,-15,15,2,9,0,0,-21,-7,-19,17,15,19,19,40,30,44,20,9,9,33,25,35,
21,23,18,41,43,41,59,75,75,54,51]} 1. b3 g6 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. c4 $1 {we start
immediately with c4 so that if Black ever plays d7-d5 (without c7-c6) we can
take cxd5} Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 c6 6. Nf3 d5 7. O-O {Welcome to our chess
journey into the Fianchetto Gruenfeld style variation! This is where the fun
begins. Instead of boring memorization, we'll enter into the exciting
strategies behind each move. We'll walk you through the common moves,
explaining the smart ideas behind them and how to respond as White. And to
spice things up, we'll explore some model games after each of Black's moves,
so you can see these strategies in action.} a5 {This move is the most popular
choice at the highest level. Black aims to expand on the queenside and
prepares for a5-a4, employing the strategic concept known as the 'signal of
attack.' Aaron Nimzowitsch brilliantly articulated this idea around a century
ago in his seminal work, 'My System.'} ({We begin with the moves Nbd7 and Re8.
In both cases, Black's idea is to play e7-e5} 7... Nbd7 8. a4 $1 {a4! It's a
move we will play only now. Why? Let's follow the logic: a4 weakens the b4
square, which could allow Black to capitalize by playing a7-a5 and Na6-Nb4.
However, since Black has already developed the knight to d7, exploiting the b4
square becomes less feasible. But what are the benefits of playing a4?
Generally, White aims to seize space on the queenside, with the potential for
moves like Ba3. However, the most crucial aspect is preventing Black from
playing b7-b5. In fact, if White starts with 8.d4, Black has the strong
response 8...b5!. So 8.a4 is also preventing Black from playing b7-b5} (8. d4
b5 $1 $11) 8... a5 (8... Re8 9. d4 Ne4 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Nf6 12. Ne5 $14)
9. d4 {Since we've stopped Black from playing b7-b5, thanks to the inclusion
of a4-a5, it's time for our next move: d2-d4. It's pretty straightforward:
Black wants to play e7-e5, so we block that with d2-d4} Ne4 10. Nbd2 {White is
typically slightly better in these positions, but let's check what happens if
Black plays in a concrete way} (10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Nb6 $1 $11) 10... Nxd2 (
10... Ndf6 11. Ne5 $14) 11. Qxd2 dxc4 12. bxc4 e5 $5 13. Qc2 exd4 14. Nxd4 Nc5
15. Rad1 Qb6 16. Ba3 Re8 17. Rb1 Qa7 18. e3 $14) (7... Re8 {now a4 would be
less logical, because Black's knight is still on b8, so it will be easier for
him to play a5-Na6-Nb4 with a fine game. But from the other hand we can play
the immediate 8.d4 because if now Black plays 8...b5 we can play Ne5!} 8. d4 (
8. a4 a5 $1 $11 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4]}) 8... Bf5 (8... b5 9. Ne5 $1 $14) (8...
Ne4 9. Ne5 Bf5 10. Nc3 {trans}) 9. Nc3 Ne4 10. Ne5 $1 $14 {now it's hard for
Black to play Nd7 because the d5 pawn would be hanging. This means that White
has at least a pleasant advantage. Let's follow a high-level game played by
the strong grand master Banusz Tamas in 2023} Nxc3 11. Bxc3 dxc4 {Black
understands that the d5 pawn is a problem, and because of it he cannot play
Nd7, so he decides just to trade it, but in this way White will get an extra
central pawn} 12. Nxc4 Qc8 13. e4 Bh3 14. Qc2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nd7 16. Rad1 Qc7 {
Black wants to play e7-e5 at some moment, White decided to play f2-f4 to
prevent it, that is fine, but it's not the only possible way} 17. f4 (17. Rfe1
$5 Rad8 (17... e5 18. d5 $16) 18. h4 e5 19. d5 cxd5 20. Rxd5 Nb6 21. Rxd8 Rxd8
22. Ba5 Qc5 23. Qc1 $14 {Nxb6 next}) 17... e6 18. Bb4 b6 $6 (18... Nb6 $1 {
was Balck's last chance to maintain a balanced game}) 19. e5 a5 20. Bd6 $16 {
1-0 Banusz,T (2616)-Thorhallsson,T (2392) Reykjavik op 2023 (8) and White was
dominating}) (7... dxc4 8. bxc4 c5 {By playing dxc4-bxc4-c5, Black is changing
the dynamics of the game. White has an extra central pawn, and the g2 bishop
strengthens. On the other hand, Black has now a nice c6 square for his Nb8} 9.
d3 Nc6 10. Ne5 $1 {very logical: we are activating the g2 bishop and
exchanging Black's nice Nc6} Na5 (10... Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Ne8 12. Bxg7 Nxg7 13. Nc3
$16 {White has a better bishop and an extra central pawn, and it is not clear
what Black has in exchange of it}) 11. Qc1 {here we should follow a very nice
game played by Aronian who beated Magnus Carlsen in Stavanger 2016} Qc7 12. Nd2
Ne8 13. f4 $1 Nd6 14. Bc3 {now Na5 is under pressure and White can continue
with Qa3} Rb8 15. Qa3 b6 16. Bxa5 bxa5 17. Nb3 Nb7 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 19. Nxc5 Qc7
20. d4 $16 {1-0 Aronian,L (2784)-Carlsen,M (2851) Norway Chess 4th Stavanger
2016 (8) Aronian won an important pawn and in a few moves the game}) (7... b6 {
this is an alternative way for Black to develop his light squares bishop. Now
White's main idea is to play e2-e4} 8. d4 Bb7 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Qc2 {preparing
e2-e4} e6 {a better move then 10..Rc8. Black's idea is to meet
e4-dxe4-Nxe4-Nxe4-Qxe4 with Qc7, where the e7 pawn will not be hanging} (10...
Rc8 {the most common move, but not the most precise, now White can play
immediately e2-e4} 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 c5 (12... Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 (13... Qc7
$2 14. Qxe7 $16) (13... e6 14. Rad1 Qc7 15. Qe2 c5 16. d5 Bxb2 17. Qxb2 exd5
18. cxd5 Rfe8 19. Nd2 $14) 14. Qe2 e6 15. Rad1 $16) 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 (13... Nxf6
14. d5 $16) 14. d5 e6 $1 {this is probably the only way for Black to achieve
just a slightly worse position} 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. Nd2 $14 {e6 is weak forever
so White has a risk-free advantage}) 11. Rad1 (11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13.
Qxe4 Qc7 $1 $11 {Black will be able to play c7-c5 next with an equal game})
11... Rc8 (11... Qc7 12. Bc1 $1 {an other nice idea, we will play Bf4 with
tempo on the Qc7} Rad8 13. Bf4 Qc8 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Rc1 a6 16. Qd2 $14 {
White has a nice plus thanks to his strong Bf4}) 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14.
Qxe4 Qc7 {the main difference now is that thanks to Rad1, White will be in
time to play d4-d5} 15. Qe2 c5 16. d5 $14) (7... Bg4 {this has been the most
played move} 8. d3 Nbd7 (8... Bxf3 {This is a solid decision. Black exchanges
on f3 before White has played Nbd2. Consequently, White must recapture with
Bg2, which may feel slightly out of place on f3. However, White gains the
bishop pair.} 9. Bxf3 e6 10. Nd2 Nbd7 11. Qc2 Qe7 12. Rab1 $5 {a nice move
played by the strong grandmaster Maxim Matlakov. White's idea is to play b4 in
some cases} a5 13. d4 (13. Bg2 $5 e5 14. e3 $14) 13... e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Bg2
Rfd8 16. e3 dxc4 17. bxc4 Nd3 18. Bd4 Nb4 {1-0 Matlakov,M (2689)-Fargere,F 
(2407) FRA-chT Top 12 Saint Quentin 2014 (8.4)} 19. Qb2 $1 $16) 9. Nbd2 Re8 {
Black is playing again for e7-e5. But compared to the immediate 8...Re8 or 8...
Nbd7, now his light squares bishop is already on g4, and this means that White
can win the bishops pair} 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Rc1 {
White has the bishops pair and a more pleasant position. Here I suggest to
follow a very nice game played by Levan Pantsulaia, an expert player of these
structures from the White side} e4 (13... Qa5 14. Rc2 $5 $146 Qxa2 (14... Rac8
15. Rxc8 Rxc8 16. Nxe5 $14) (14... a6 15. Qa1 $14) 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Qxb3
17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Qb1 Qxb1 19. Rxb1 $14) 14. dxe4 dxe4 15. Nd4 Qb6 16. Nc2 Rad8
17. Ne3 Ne5 18. Qc2 Nh5 {1-0 Pantsulaia,L (2595)-Baramidze,D (2614) EU-chT 
(Men) 19th Warsaw 2013 (3.7) Black is threatening Nxg3, but engine shows that
White could have just ignored it:} 19. Rfd1 $1 Nxg3 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Bxe5 Bxe5
{and now are coming the two key moves} 22. Nc4 $1 Qc5 23. b4 $1 $16 {and White
will win a piece}) 8. Nc3 $1 {a concrete move against a5-a4} Ne4 (8... Na6 9.
d4 Bf5 10. Ne5 Ne4 11. Qc1 $14) (8... d4 9. Na4 $1 Ne8 10. e3 e5 11. exd4 exd4
12. Ba3 $1 Nd6 {1-0 Matamoros Franco,C (2486)-Kamsky,G (2662) Titled Tuesday
intern op 07th Sept Chess.com INT blitz 2021 (6)} 13. Bc5 $1 {putting the
maximum pressure on the d4 pawn} d3 14. Rc1 $14 {d3 is potentially weak, as is
the b6 square, and White has better pieces}) 9. Na4 Bxb2 (9... b5 {played a
few times by the Norwegian talent GM Aryan Tari} 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. cxb5 cxb5
12. Nc3 b4 $1 $146 {and improvement for Black on the Grandelius-Tari game} (
12... Nxc3 $6 {was his choice in his game against Grandelius, but here White
is better} 13. dxc3 Nc6 14. Nd4 Na7 15. c4 $16 {½-½ Grandelius,N (2651)-Tari,
A (2634) NOR-SWE Online Blitz chess24.com INT 2020 (13.1)}) 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14.
Ng5 f5 15. d3 h6 16. Nh3 $14 {Unpleasant to play for Black}) 10. Nxb2 Na6 11.
d3 Nf6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Qd2 {White has a small but risk-free advantage.
Please note that the move a7-a5 in this scenario has only weakened some
squares on the queenside. Let's follow the game played by the young but strong
Indian grand master Nihal Sarin} Bd7 14. Rfc1 Qb6 15. Na4 $1 {Nihal shows a
great strategic understanding! If Black plays Bxa4, after bxa4, he will have
problems on the b line} Qd6 (15... Bxa4 16. bxa4 Rfc8 17. Rab1 Rxc1+ 18. Qxc1
$14) 16. Qxa5 Nb4 17. Qc7 $16 {White was better and managed to win the game in
Nihal Sarin- Iskandarov, M Belgrade Open 2021. CONCLUSIONS: When Black plays
in the Symmetrical Gruenfeld style, he ends up with a solid but somewhat
passive position. The challenge for White in this scenario is that Black has
many options at move 8, and each choice leads to a different type of position.
The key is to grasp the main ideas behind each of Black's moves and understand
the basic strategies for White. I really hope that after studying this chapter,
you now feel ready to understand these ideas and play these positions
successfully as White!} *

