1. b3 g6 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. c4 {In the previous chapter, we looked into what
happens when Black goes for the c6-d5 setup (Symmetrical Gruenfeld style).
Let's delve into what occurs when Black immediately plays d7-d5 without first
playing c7-c6 (Pure Gruenfeld style). This chapter highlights the importance
of starting with 3.c4: it enables White to counter Black's d7-d5 with cxd5} Bg7
(3... d5 {if Black plays d5 before having played Bg7-00, then after cxd5 he
must take back with the queen} 4. cxd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qd8 (5... Qa5 6. Nf3 Bg7 7.
g3 O-O 8. Bg2 Rd8 (8... e5 9. O-O e4 10. Ne1 Re8 11. d3 $14) 9. O-O c5 (9...
Nc6 10. d3 Nd5 11. Na4 Bxb2 12. Nxb2 $14 {White will continue with Nc4-Ne5})
10. Ne5 $14 {without allowing Black to continue with Nc6}) (5... Qh5 $6 {
doesn't make sense if White still hasn't played g2-g3} 6. e4 $1 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1
Bg7 (7... c6 8. d4 Bg7 9. Bd3 $14) 8. Nd5 $16) 6. g3 Bg7 7. Bg2 O-O (7... c5 8.
Nf3 Nc6 9. Na4 $1 Qd6 10. Rc1 b6 11. d4 $16) 8. Nf3 c5 (8... Nc6 9. d4 $14) 9.
O-O Nc6 10. Na4 $1 {thanks to this, and only to this move, Black is not in
time to complete his development} Qd6 (10... b6 11. d4 $1 $16) 11. Rc1 b6 12.
d4 $16) 4. g3 O-O (4... d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 {comparing to 3...d5, the difference
is that now Black can play with Qh5, which makes more sense when White has
already played g2-g3} 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Bg2 Nc6 (7... Qh5 8. h3 $1 (8. O-O $6 Bh3
$11 {and Black is completely fine}) 8... Nc6 9. d3 Rd8 10. Nbd2 a5 11. a3 $14 {
White will continue with useful move such as Rc1-Qc2}) 8. d3 $1 {White can
wait one or two moves before playing 00, so that Qh5 makes less sense because
until the rook is on h1, White can always play h3} (8. O-O Qh5 $1) 8... Rd8 9.
Nbd2 Qh5 10. h3 $14) 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 {only when Black has already
played Bg7-00, he can take back on d5 with Nf6} 7. Bxg7 Kxg7 {now White should
play a little bit creative in order to create some problems for the opponent}
8. Qc2 $5 {with the idea to play Nc3} ({the logical} 8. Nf3 {doesn't promise
much after} Nc6 $1 9. d4 (9. O-O e5 $11) 9... Bg4 10. O-O Qd6 11. e4 Nb6 12. d5
Ne5 13. Qd4 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qf6 15. Nd2 Nxf3+ 16. Nxf3 Qxd4 17. Nxd4 Rfd8 $11)
8... Nc6 (8... Re8 $5 9. d4 (9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. Qxc3+ e5 $11) 9... Nc6 10. Nf3 e5
11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Rxe5 13. O-O Qf6 14. e4 $14 {White has the potential of
f4-e5}) (8... f6 9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 e5 11. Rd1 $14 {d4 next}) 9. Nc3 Nxc3 (
9... Ndb4 10. Qb2 Nd4 11. Rd1 Qd6 (11... Nbc2+ $2 12. Kf1 $16 {Black is
running serious risks to lose on of his knights}) 12. Nf3 Rd8 13. O-O Nxf3+ 14.
Bxf3 Qd4 15. Bg2 c6 16. a3 Nd5 17. e3 Qf6 18. d4 Nxc3 19. Qxc3 $14) 10. Qxc3+
Qd4 11. Rc1 Qxc3 12. Rxc3 Bd7 13. f4 $5 $14 {Nf3 next with a pleasant endgame
for White thanks to his extra central pawn} *

