1. b3 g6 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 c5 6. Nf3 d6 7. d4 {if Black
plays with 7...Ne4 or with 7...Nc6, as he usually does, then we are
transposing into Chapter 12. What we have to check now is what happens if
Black is playing cxd4-Nxd4 followed by the "strange" waste of tempo d6-d5! I
can say immediately that this is considered one of the critical lines
according to the nowadays state of theory} cxd4 (7... Ne4 8. O-O Nc6 {[%emt 0:
00:12] trans in Chapter}) (7... Nc6 8. O-O {[%emt 0:00:12] trans in Chapter}) (
7... d5 {this is the move suggested by Gaiwain Jones. Black is aiming for a
fast liquidation in the center. Here in my opinion the only challenging
continuation is Nbd2} 8. Nbd2 $1 {very logical: if Black plays dxc4, White
wants to take back with the knight. For this reason, Black's best now is the
other capture, cxd4} (8. O-O dxc4 {and Black should be able to equalize}) (8.
cxd5 Nxd5 $11) 8... cxd4 {The key idea here is that White intends to capture
on d4 only after Black has deployed his knight to c6. Why? Because if White
would capture immediately with Nxd4, Black could counter with e5! However, if
Black's knight is already on c6, then after Nxd4-e5, White can respond with
Nxc6} (8... dxc4 9. Nxc4 $14) 9. O-O $1 (9. Bxd4 Nc6 10. Bb2 e5 $1 11. Nxe5 $2
Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Re8 $17 {Black has too much development}) (9. Nxd4 $6 e5 $1 $15)
9... Nc6 {the move suggested by Jones, and probably Black's best} (9... Re8 {
a waiting move, but the inclusion of 00 and Re8 is for sure in White's favour:}
10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd4 {White wants to continue with Nc4, so Black should try
to play fast} Nf4 $1 12. gxf4 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 Qxd4 14. e3 $14 {White will
continue with Nc4 enjoying a pleasant position thanks to his better Bg2}) (9...
d3 {played in the majority of the games, but here White gets a favourable
position} 10. exd3 Nc6 (10... b6 {Jussupow- Radjabov, here I like the
following plan:} 11. b4 $1 Bb7 12. a4 {White intends to continue with a5} a5
13. b5 $16 {Black's b6 pawn is a potential weakness, and White is
strategically better here}) 11. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Bg4 13. Qc2 Qd7 {was
played in the game Meier-Andriasian here White has played d3-d4, but I prefer
to play a move like Rfe1-followed by Qb2 with full control on the e5 square}
14. Rfe1 Rac8 15. Qb2 $14) 10. Nxd4 Bd7 $5 $146 {again we are following Jones'
recommendation} (10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Be6 12. c5 $14 {White has long term
chances thanks to the queenside majority}) 11. e3 $5 {consolidating Nd4 and
intending cxd5 next} Bg4 $1 {Black's most precise reaction} 12. Qc1 Rc8 13.
Nxc6 bxc6 {Jones' asses this position as equal, and he is probably right in a
higher sense, but White can still pose some problems} (13... Rxc6 14. Be5 $14 {
Qb2 next}) 14. Re1 $1 {with the idea to play e3-e4} Bf5 {looks the more
logical, trying to exchange the light-squares bishops one White playes e3-e4}
15. e4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 e6 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qa3 $14 {
Black is solid, but White has a better pawn structure on the queenside, and
for this reason we can press even against the players that have studied
carefully the wonderful job of Jones Gaiwain}) 8. Nxd4 d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. O-O
{Black has two good moves now: Qa5 and Nb4} Nb4 (10... e5 $2 11. Nb5 Be6 12.
Bxd5 Bxd5 13. Ba3 $18 {White is already winning}) (10... a6 11. Qc1 $1 $16 {
White will play Rd1 next with already a good advantage}) (10... Na6 {
Wojtaszek-Krasenkow 2019} 11. Qd2 $1 $16 {White wants to play as fast as
possible Rd1, and it's clear that White pieces are much more active}) (10...
Qa5 {according to the current state of theory, this move equalizes, but I'm
suggesting a new move posing some problems to the Black player} 11. e3 $5 $146
{more ambitious} (11. Qd2 {White can go for a safe endgame after} Qxd2 12. Nxd2
Rd8 13. Rfd1 Bxd4 14. Bxd4 Nc6 15. Bb2 {White has a more pleasant position,
even if it's not clear if this is enough for a real advantage}) 11... e5 $1 {
this is Black's best move for concrete reasons, but from a positional point of
view now his Bg7 will be a little bit passive} (11... Rd8 12. Na3 $1 Nb6 13.
Qe2 $14) (11... Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd4+ $14 {typically
slightly better for White thanks to the better pawn structure}) 12. Nb5 $3 {
the key move} Qxb5 ({it would be too risky for Black to take the pawn} 12...
Nxe3 $6 13. fxe3 Qxb5 14. Nc3 $16 {White will play Nd5 next; even for the
engine, it is not clear if Black can survive against such active White's pieces
}) 13. Na3 {we play another developing move before taking back on d5} Qa6 $1 (
13... Qa5 $6 14. Nc4 $1 {gives even extra tempi for White} Qc7 15. Qxd5 Nc6 16.
Qd6 $14 {very unpleasant for Black}) 14. Qxd5 Nc6 15. Qc4 {White would like to
exchange queens on c4, so that Na3 will become a fantastic piece on c4} ({
White can force a queen exchange with} 15. Qb5 Qxb5 16. Nxb5 {but now Nb5 is a
little bit misplaced} Rd8 $1 {still more pleasant for White but Black can hold
with a few precise moves}) 15... Qb6 $1 {but Black shouldn't go to the endgame,
and he plays Qb6 now that Nc4 is not available because our queen is on that
square} (15... Qxc4 16. Nxc4 $14) 16. Qa4 (16. Qh4 $5 Be6 17. Nc4 Qc7 18. Ba3
Rfd8 19. Rad1 {a little bit unpleasant for Black}) 16... Be6 (16... Bd7 17.
Rad1 Rfd8 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. Ba3 $1 $36 {looks a little bit scary but in fact
White wants Bd6 next and Black doesn't have great ideas here}) 17. Rac1 Rac8
18. Nb5 $5 {going for the d6 square} Rfd8 19. Ba3 $1 Bf8 20. Bxf8 Kxf8 21. Qa3+
Kg7 22. Nd6 Rc7 23. Ne4 $14 {Qb2-Nc5 or Ng5 next and White has some initiative}
) 11. Na3 N8c6 $1 (11... N8a6 12. Nc4 Rb8 13. a3 Nd5 14. b4 $1 $16 {it is easy
to understand who has the better pieces here}) (11... Qa5 $6 {going under} 12.
Nc4 {with tempo} Qh5 {Black hopes to achieve something on the kingside, but he
is too much behind in development} 13. Qd2 N8c6 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16.
Qc3+ f6 17. Qe3 $16) (11... e5 {as we have seen already this move gains space
but blocks a little bit the Bg7} 12. Ndb5 $1 N8c6 13. Nc4 $14 {White is going
for the d6 square}) 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qc2 $14 {
objectively speaking Black can hold, but from a practical point of view it is
very unpleasant to play such positions from the Black side as the c6 pawn will
be a weakness forever} *

