{[%evp 0,13,30,-16,6,5,12,-11,-11,-29,-13,-13,-1,9,28,36]} 1. b3 g6 2. Bb2 Nf6
3. c4 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. d4 {In this Chapter, we will check how to
deal when Black plays in the style of the King's Indian defense (KID)} e5 (6...
c5 {trans in next Chapter}) (6... Nc6 7. Nf3 e5 (7... a6 {Black tries to play
in Panno style} 8. d5 $1 Na5 9. Nbd2 $16 {thanks to White's construction
b4+c4+Nbd2, Na5 is pretty passive, comparing to the classical "Panno systems"
in KID. In those setups, the knight on a5 typically exhibits some pressure
against White's c4 pawn.}) 8. d5 Ne7 9. Nc3 Nd7 {logically Black tries to play
f7-f5 in true KID style} 10. O-O h6 (10... f5 $2 11. Ng5 $1 Nf6 12. e4 h6 13.
Ne6 $1 $16) 11. e4 f5 12. exf5 $1 gxf5 13. Nh4 $1 {White will play f2-f4 next}
a5 {securing the c5 square for Nc5, so that White cannot play b3-b4} 14. f4 e4
15. Rf2 $1 $16 {this is called the "Botvinnik plan". White wants to play
Bf1-Ng2-Ne3 and slowly break on the kingside with h3-h4}) (6... Nbd7 7. e3 $1 {
now we go for Ne2 development} (7. Nf3 e5 $1 8. dxe5 dxe5 {with an equal game,
the e5 pawn is not hanging as after} 9. Nxe5 $2 {Black has} Ng4 $1 $17) 7... e5
8. Ne2 Re8 9. Nbc3 c6 (9... e4 10. Qc2 Qe7 11. h3 $1 {White goest for g3-g4} h5
12. g4 $1 hxg4 13. hxg4 Nxg4 14. Qxe4 Qxe4 15. Bxe4 $14 {our extra central
pawn gives us a pleasant endgame}) 10. d5 $1 (10. O-O $6 e4 $1 $15 {and Black
gets some play on the light squares}) 10... c5 11. e4 $16) 7. dxe5 Nfd7 (7...
Ng4 {is the most common move, but White gets a typical pleasant play} 8. Nc3
Nxe5 9. Nf3 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Nc6 11. Bg2 (11. O-O Bh3 $5) 11... Re8 12. O-O $14 {
White will simply continue with Qd2-Rfe1-Rad1, and at some moment in the
future Nd5}) (7... dxe5 $5 $146 {fine according to engines, but Black should
know exactly what he is doing} 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxe5 Re8 $1 10. Bc3 a5 $1 {
only with these two moves, Re8, and a5, Black has some compensation for the
pawn, according to the engine. I don't think we need to analyze any further.
We can just continue with normal development moves like Nf3-Nd2 and check if
our opponent wants to play with pawn down}) 8. Nc3 dxe5 $1 {the key concept,
Black should take back with the pawn} 9. Qd2 $1 {White wants to play a fast
Rd1 taking full control on the 'd' line} Nc5 $1 {Black should challenge
immediately the 'd' line} (9... c6 $2 {happened in my game against Neiksans,
2018} 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Ne4 $1 a5 12. Nf3 $16) 10. Qe3 $5 {without allowing the
queen exchange} Nbd7 11. Rd1 c6 12. Ba3 Qb6 13. Nh3 $14 {Black still needs to
solve some problems with the development. Objectively, Black's position is
fine, but we still have some initiative} *

