1. b3 g6 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 c5 6. Nf3 {In Chapter 7, we
explored the implications of White adopting a Gruenfeld-style approach, opting
for d5 without including c6. Meanwhile, Chapter 6 delved into the analysis of
the Symmetrical Gruenfeld style, characterized by the moves c6 followed by d5.
Now, let's turn our attention to examining the "English style" variation,
where Black plays with c5 followed by d5. This setup can occur with or without
the inclusion of Nc6. Fundamentally, we recognize that if Black responds with
c5 followed by d5, the resulting position can render the c5 pawn vulnerable
after the exchange cxd5. This vulnerability stems from the fact that the
d-pawn can no longer defend the c5 pawn, and advancing b7 to b6 might expose
Black to challenges along the h1-a8 diagonal. While Black can seek to defend
the pawn with moves like Qd6, White retains the opportunity to apply rapid
pressure through moves such as Rc1, Nc3, and Na4. In conclusion, the crux of
this variation lies in whether White can effectively exploit the vulnerability
of the c5 pawn.} Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Qxd5 ({Black can go for} 7... Nxd5 8.
Bxg7 Kxg7 9. O-O {where Nc6 would transpose into 6...Nc6, while a move like 6..
.Nf6 doesn't bring Black anything good} Nc6 {Would transpose to 7... d5} (9...
Nf6 $6 10. Qc2 $1 Na6 11. Qb2 $14)) 8. Nc3 Qd6 (8... Qf5 9. Na4 $1 {As already
explained, the key in this position is to attack the c5 pawn} Nc6 {
Adhiban-Schevchenko} 10. Nh4 $1 $146 Qh5 11. Rc1 $16 {and c5 is falling}) (8...
Qh5 9. h3 $1 $16 {As explored in the "Pure Gruenfeld" chapter, when Black opts
for Qh5, White possesses the option to respond with h3, particularly if
castling kingside (0-0) hasn't yet occurred.}) 9. O-O Nc6 10. Rc1 Bg4 $1 (10...
b6 $6 {a common mistake, now White can break immediately with} 11. d4 $1 Rd8
12. Qe1 $1 $146 {taking away the queen from the 'd' line} Bb7 13. Nb5 Qd7 14.
dxc5 bxc5 15. Rxc5 Ne4 16. Rc2 Bxb2 17. Rxb2 $14 {White has a healthy extra
pawn}) 11. Nb5 Qd8 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Qb6 14. Nc3 Rac8 15. d3 {next Rc2-Qa1
with a little bit more pleasant position for White}) 7. O-O d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 (
8... Qxd5 $2 {now this is just losing} 9. Ne5 $1 Qd6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. d3 $16 {
White is strategically winning: he can continue with Nd2-Rc1 and the c5 pawn
will fall at some moment}) 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. d4 cxd4 (10... Qb6 $2 {allows} 11.
e4 Nf6 12. d5 Nd4 13. e5 $18 {when Nxd5 is not possible because of
Nxd4-cxd4-Bxd5}) 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 (11... Qb6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Nd2 Ba6 {
Rozum-Ponkratov 2023} 14. Rc1 $1 Rfd8 15. Nc4 Qc5 16. Qc2 $14 {White has a
risk-free advantage thanks to the strongest bishop and Black's weak c6 pawn}) (
11... e5 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qc2 Qb6 14. Nc3 $16) (11... Ndb4 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 13.
Bxc6 bxc6 {engine evaluates just +0,40, but in practice, out of 40 games,
White has scored here the 90%! This means that in a practical game this
position is very unpleasant to defend for Black. White will just play moves
like Nc3-Rc1-Na4-Nc5 and Black's c6 wekaness will be so forever. Let's follow
a nice game played by the Croatian GM Ante Saric} 14. Nc3 Bh3 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8
16. Rfd1 Rac8 17. f3 $1 {bringing the king close to the center} Be6 18. Rxd8
Rxd8 19. Kf2 c5 20. Ne4 c4 21. b4 $1 Bf5 {now Saric Ante has played Rc1, and
won anyway the game, but would have been better for White to play} 22. Nc3 $1 (
22. Rc1 Bxe4 23. fxe4 {Saric, A - Gschnitzer 2020}) 22... Rd2 23. a4 Rb2 24. g4
Be6 25. b5 $16 {White will continue with Ke3-Kd4 with a very hard-to-defend
endgame for Black. If Black plays Rb3, White can defend the knight with Ra3 if
Black plays Rb3, while White can defend with Rc1}) (11... Nc3 $5 {very rare
but not a bad move for Black: he will just get a slightly worse endgame} 12.
Nxc3 Qxd4 13. Qxd4+ Nxd4 14. Rfd1 Rd8 15. Kf1 {here we should follow a great
game played by Tony Miles in 1988!} Ne6 16. Nd5 (16. f4 $1 $14 {was
objectively better for White}) 16... Kf8 17. Rac1 Rb8 18. Ke1 Rd6 19. Nf4 Nxf4
20. gxf4 Rxd1+ 21. Kxd1 Ke8 22. Kd2 Kd8 23. Bd5 e6 24. Be4 b6 25. h4 h5 26. Bd3
Bb7 27. e4 Kd7 28. Bb5+ Kd8 29. Ke3 Bc8 30. Kd4 Bd7 31. Bxd7 Kxd7 32. Ke5 $18 {
1-0 Miles,A (2500)-Hoeksema,H (2355) Dieren op 1988 (2)}) 12. Qxd4+ Nf6 13. Qe5
{we have reached a symmetrical position, where White has a more active queen
and a better light-squares bishop} Qd6 {a sad move to play, but objectively
the best} (13... a5 14. Nc3 Ra6 {was tried by Aronian} 15. Rfd1 {but here
Black had to play} Re6 $1 16. Qxe6 fxe6 (16... Bxe6 $2 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Bxb7
$16) 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Kf1 $14 {Ke1 next with a very unpleasant endgame for
Black}) (13... Qb6 $2 {the most common move, but here White gets the advantage}
14. Nc3 Be6 15. Na4 Qb4 16. Nc5 $16) 14. Qxd6 exd6 15. Rd1 Rd8 16. Nc3 {
the endgame is unpleasant for Black, but still holdable} Rb8 $3 {the best move,
but a hard move to be played, as Black should know what to do against Nb5} (
16... a6 $6 {has been the most common move, but it's already a mistake} 17. Rd2
Kf8 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 Ra7 20. Rc1 b5 21. Rdc2 $16 {White has a better pawn
structure and the 'c' line}) 17. e3 $5 (17. Nb5 d5 $1 18. Nxa7 Bd7 $1 19. a4
Ra8 20. Nb5 Bxb5 21. axb5 Rxa1 22. Rxa1 Rc8 $1 {and according to engine Black
is just in time to equalize}) 17... a6 18. Rd2 Kf8 19. h3 $5 $14 {White will
continue with Ne2-Nd4 with a very pleasant endgame} *

