1. b3 g6 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O d6 8. d4 {
White is ready to push d4-d5, so Black needs to do something about it} cxd4 (
8... Bg4 {Black shouldn't play moves like this because after} 9. d5 $16 {
White is just much better from a strategical point of view}) (8... Ne4 {
Black is playing against the Bb2} 9. e3 {White defends the d4 pawn and wants
to continue now with Qc1-d5} Bg4 $1 {this is the most logical play, Black is
preparing some counterplay against Qc1} (9... Qa5 10. Qc1 $1 {defending Bb2
and preparing d4-d5} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. exd4 Nf6 13. Re1 Re8 14. Nd2 $14)
10. Qc1 Bxf3 $1 {if not this White just continues with d5} 11. Bxf3 Ng5 $1 {
Black attacks both the d4 pawn and the f3 bishop, now White needs to give some
concessions} (11... f5 $2 12. d5 $16) 12. Bxc6 {a move that we are not happy
to play, but we have to play} bxc6 13. dxc5 Qd7 $1 $146 {Black has to go
"all-in" on the kingside} (13... Bxb2 14. Qxb2 dxc5 15. Nc3 $14) (13... dxc5
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Nc3 $14 {White is definitely slightly better thanks to the
more healthy pawn structure}) 14. Bxg7 Nf3+ 15. Kg2 Nh4+ $1 16. Kh1 (16. gxh4
Qg4+ 17. Kh1 Qf3+ $11) 16... Qh3 17. Rg1 Nf3 18. Rg2 Kxg7 19. cxd6 {now Black
has to be very fast, if White can just play Nd2 he will be winning} Rfd8 $1 (
19... exd6 $2 20. Nd2 $16) 20. dxe7 (20. Nd2 Nxd2 21. Qxd2 Rxd6 $11) 20... Rd7
{White has 2 extra pawns, but cannot now play Nd2} 21. Nc3 Qe6 $1 22. Ne2 Qxe7
23. Qc3+ Kg8 24. Ng1 $5 {we want to exchange that knight at all costs} Nxg1 (
24... Qe4 25. Qf6 $14) 25. Kxg1 Rad8 26. Re1 Rd1 27. h4 $44 {White has an
extra pawn but Rg2 is out of the game for the moment. White would like to
continue with Kh2-Rg1. Engine thinks that Black here almost equalized; in a
practical game, Black still needs to be a little bit precise to not let White
activate the g2 rook}) (8... d5 $5 {This is the same position analyzed in
Chapter 10, only that White has included the move d2-d4. Strangely enough,
this move could go into Black's favor now, even if the Bb2 is not
participating directly in the game for a moment.} 9. Nbd2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4
11. Bxd4 Be6 $1 12. c5 $5 {changing structure, now we will play for the
queenside majority. It's important to note that for Black is very difficult to
play e7-e5} Qd7 13. Nf3 a5 14. Rc1 $14 {We have reached a fighting position,
where White has the more pleasant side. He can continue with moves like
Qc2-Ne5-Nd3 and slowly prepare a3-b4-b5. It will not be easy, but from the
other side, Black doesn't have a clear plan to prevent White from expanding on
the queenside.}) 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Qd2 $5 {I like this waiting-useful move
because as White we want to be able to take back on d4 with Bb2} (10. Nc3 Nxd4
$1 11. Qxd4 Bc6 {maybe White can press a bit here, but Black is almost
completely fine}) 10... a6 $1 {a better waiting move comparing to 10...Rc8,
because now after Nc3-Nxd4-Qxd4 the a7 pawn is not hanging anymore} (10... Nxd4
11. Bxd4 $1 Bc6 12. Nc3 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 $14 {and comparing to the 10.Nc3 above
line, here White has a better version as his d4 bishop is stronger. I suggest
checking the Grachev-Kokarev game to understand a little bit the spirit of the
position} a6 14. a4 e6 15. Rfd1 Qc7 16. Rac1 Rfd8 17. f3 Rac8 18. e4 Ne8 19.
Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qd4+ Kg8 21. Rd3 Qc5 22. Rcd1 Qxd4 23. Rxd4 Kf8 24. a5 Ke7 25.
Na4 e5 26. R4d2 f5 27. Nb6 Rc6 28. f4 $1 $16 {1-0 Grachev,B (2615)-Kokarev,D 
(2605) RUS-chT 26th Sochi 2019 (9.4)}) (10... Rc8 {Black plays a waiting move,
hoping for Nc3 where after Nxd4 White will have to take back with the queen}
11. Nc3 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 $14 {but now the problem is that both the a7 and b7
pawns are hanging}) 11. Nc2 $5 (11. Nc3 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Bc6 $11) 11... b5 12. Ne3
Rb8 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Rc1 $14 {White still has the more pleasant side, but at
least here Black is more or less fine objectively} *

