{[%evp 0,20,31,-19,-32,-25,-14,-32,-26,-38,-23,-31,-38,-17,-42,-13,4,5,11,42,
37,33,46]} 1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. Nf3 {In the course, we focus on 3.e3, but
this line is also a poisonous idea, as players prepare less for this move and
there is not so much theory.} e4 {The strongest reply} (3... d6 $6 {an
inferior choice, as we strike immediately} 4. d4 $1 e4 5. d5 $1 {a usual
strong reaction that we recognize also from other lines}) 4. Nd4 Nxd4 5. Bxd4
d5 6. e3 Nf6 {Both players make the most natural moves in the position,
developing the pieces. Now it is time for White to undermine the center.} (6...
h5 $1 {The strong engine suggestion, followed by computer lines, where Black
can maybe claim equality.}) 7. c4 $1 {Now we transpose to our repertoire} Be7 (
7... c5 $2 {Very grave positional mistake.} 8. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 9. Nc3 $1 {And the
best reaction for Black is to give up the pawn with ...d4, as Black totally
collapses on the light squares otherwise.}) (7... c6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. cxd5 cxd5
10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. O-O O-O {with a good position for White} 13. f3
{½-½ Bernadskiy,V (2617)-Ceres,D (2380) Lancenigo op 2022 (2)} (13. d3 $5 {
another interesting idea})) 8. Nc3 dxc4 {The best moment to take.} (8... c6 9.
cxd5 cxd5 {transposes}) (8... O-O 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe4 {Maybe Black has some
compensation, but for sure White is for choice.}) 9. Bxc4 {The most natural
way to recapture.} (9. bxc4 $5 {Another interesting try for White.} c5 10. Be5
$1 {We dont trade on f6 now as Black recaptures with the bishop instead of the
queen, and black is in time to neutralize the knight due to the pin} O-O 11.
Rb1 Re8 12. Nb5 $1 {With a pleasant initiative connected with Nc7 or
Bxf6-Nc7-Nd5 ideas.}) 9... O-O 10. O-O c6 {Multipurpose move, controling d5
and also preparing b5} 11. Qc2 {White focuses on developing the queen with
tempo} b5 $1 {Important inclusion.} (11... Bf5 {A naive way of playing, as it
just runs into} 12. f3 $1 {And Black just loses the pawn.}) 12. Be2 Bf5 {
And now this is possible as ...exf3 is possible for Black now, due to the
bishop on e2.} 13. Rad1 {White has to challenge the pawn on e4, so as the f3
method is out of the picture, White plays, preparing d3, avoiding potential
troubles on the d-file} (13. d3 $4 exd3 14. Bxd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 c5 {White just
loses a piece.}) 13... Re8 14. d3 {White is now in time to achieve his
strategical goals, and even though the opponent went fast for this position,
and was clearly in preparation, White still enjoys a comfortable position.}
exd3 15. Bxd3 Bxd3 16. Rxd3 Qa5 {Black is still playing very fast, which means
he is in his opening preparation.} 17. Rfd1 Rac8 {Supporting the c6 pawn.} 18.
h3 {Now begins a series of waiting moves, as Black doesnt really want to go ...
c5 because Bxf6 and Nd5 is a strong reaction, while White doesnt really want
to go e4 because ...c5! and the d4 becomes weakened.} h6 {Black isnt falling
for it.} (18... c5 $6 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Nd5 $14 {With a very pleasant position
and central control.}) 19. R3d2 {Still waiting.} Rcd8 {And now it is the
crucial moment for White, as visually the useful moves are over. Can you find
Whites best continuation?} 20. Ne2 $6 {A clear mistake, as now White loses
control of the d5 square and Black is in time to react in the center.} (20. Kf1
$3 {The brilliant waiting move, also hinting that in a soon to be endgame,
Whites king is close to e2 square (thats why f1 and not h1).} a6 {If black
continues to wait, then:} (20... Qa6 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Ne4 $14) 21. Bxf6 Rxd2
22. Qxd2 Bxf6 23. Ne4 $1 Qxd2 24. Nxf6+ gxf6 25. Rxd2 {And the endgame is
advantageous for White due to the close king.}) (20. Bxf6 Rxd2 21. Qxd2 Bxf6
22. Ne4 Qxd2 23. Nxf6+ gxf6 24. Rxd2 c5 $1 {and here Black can hold the endgame
}) 20... c5 $1 {Solves everything now for Black, and the game soon settled.}
21. Bc3 (21. Bxf6 Rxd2 22. Rxd2 Bxf6 23. Nf4 {If White aims for the d5 square,
it allows some counterplay.} Be5 24. Nd5 c4 $1 $132 {And Black is creating a
very dangerous passed pawn.}) 21... Qc7 22. Ng3 Rxd2 23. Rxd2 Bd6 24. Ba5 Qc6
25. Nf5 Bf8 26. Rd1 Ne4 1/2-1/2

