1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 {Now, White choses the 3.e3 line, and we are in our
repertoire.} Nf6 4. Nf3 e4 5. Nd4 Nxd4 6. Bxd4 Be7 7. c4 O-O 8. Nc3 c5 {
All theory for now.} 9. Be5 {Clearly, we don't give up the pair of bishops.} (
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Rc1 Bxc3 {After any recapture, the position is very close to
equal.}) 9... d6 10. Bg3 Bf5 {Black supports the e4 pawn, to break in the
center with ...d5.} 11. Bh4 {We try to stop it.} Nd7 {Most natural way to
continue, releasing the tension of the unpleasant pin.} (11... d5 {is still
possible for Black, but the arising position is very unpleasant for Black,
pawn down and trying to make a draw all the game.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. cxd5 Qa5
14. Qc2 {1-0 Jobava,B (2588)-Abdrlauf,E (2343) Titled Tuesday intern op 01st
Feb-B Chess.com INT blitz 2022 (7)}) 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Now it is an important
moment for White.} 13. d4 $1 {Strongest reaction, as we are inviting both
recaptures.} (13. Be2 $6 Ne5 {And Black is absolutely fine, as the d2 pawn
remains stuck.}) (13. d3 {not so precise, as Black ignores the pawn.} Nf6 $1 {
Rad8-Rfe8 next} (13... exd3 14. Bxd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Rad8 16. Rd1 {This would be
a dream scenario for White.}) 14. dxe4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 {And we are not in
time to develop.}) 13... Nb6 {A sign of panic from the opponent, as it is
clear that the knight is a very bad piece on b6.} (13... Nf6 {Was a better
square.}) 14. a4 $1 {A multipurpose move, of course we want to play a5, but we
also invite the ...a5 move from Black so when the move d4-d5 happens, we have
no problems on the queenside as it is all locked, and we just try to crush the
opponent on the kingside.} a5 15. Qd2 {Good move, hiding the intention of
where White wants to castle. There was nothing wrong with d5 either.} Rfd8 {
Now Black wants to break open with ...d5.} 16. d5 $1 {Of course, we close it,
and now the rook on d8 is completely useless.} Bg6 17. h4 {We grab space, and
make it clear that we want to castle long.} Bh5 {Logical move to try and stop
the advance, and also to trade the bishops on e2, but it is not clear if it is
best, as we will see Black will have a lot of problems on the light squares on
the future so the bishop on g6 was a good defending piece.} 18. Be2 {We invite
the trade.} Bxe2 19. Qxe2 f5 {Sooner or later Black has to play it anyway, as
the e4 is quite weak.} 20. f4 $1 {Strategical understanding that the only good
available square for the moment for Black is the e5 square for the knight, so
we stop immediately and ask him to decide.} exf3 {The lesser evil.} (20... Nd7
21. g4 $1 {The only move in the position, as otherwise the knight gets to f6
and Black is in time to close the position completely.}) 21. gxf3 Re8 22. Kd2 {
We are not scared, as Black's pieces still don't have any potential.} Qf6 {
Now Black prepares f4 with great effect.} (22... f4 $5 {Maybe it was already
time for Black to sacrifice a pawn to get some activity, but White is for
choice after both accepting the offer with exf4 or the more direct Ne4 to put
pressure on the d6 pawn.}) 23. f4 $1 {Now Black is totally helpless, with no
chance for counterplay, has to only sit and wait.} Re7 24. Rh3 Nd7 25. Rg1 {
We improve the rooks.} Nb8 {Probably Black wanted to transfer the knight to b4,
but it doesnt do much there either.} 26. Qd1 {Good prophylaxis, and we also
want to trade queens with Qa1-Nb5 in some cases.} Nd7 {Black just waits.} (
26... Na6 27. Qa1 {[%cal Gc3b5]}) 27. Rg5 {White is in no hurry.} Rf7 28. Kc2
Re8 29. Qd3 h6 {Dubious decision, to weaken further the g6 square, but on the
other hand its hard to come up with any move for Black, and White has a lot of
ideas at his disposal.} 30. Rg1 Nf8 31. h5 {The position is just strategically
lost for Black.} b6 32. Rhg3 Ree7 33. Nb1 {To reroute the knight and also to
trade queens, as the endgame is hopeless for Black.} Qh4 34. Qf1 {We
indirectly protect the pawn.} Rd7 (34... Qxh5 $4 35. Rh1 $18) 35. Nd2 Nh7 36.
Nf3 Qe7 37. Qd3 {In a few moves, White beautifully transfered the knight from
c3 to f3, closer to the action.} Qe4 38. Nh4 {Trading on d3 is more favorable,
as the f5 weakness remains on the board.} Qxd3+ 39. Kxd3 {White achieved the
endgame, and even if it looks holdable, Black is lost.} Nf8 40. Ke2 Rf6 41. Kf3
{We place the king on an ideal square.} Re7 42. Ng6 $4 {A tough to explain
decision, maybe due to the nerves of the World Cup, but after this the
position is draw.} (42. R3g2 $1 {And the plan of Re2-e4 is completely crushing
for White, as soon as the knight leaves f8, we will go with the other rook to
g6, trade one pair, return to h4 with the knight, and anyway e4 is crushing.}
Ra7 43. Re2 Nh7 44. Rg6 {The evaluation is +3, but on human terms is just
completely lost.} Raf7 45. Reg2 Nf8 46. Rxf6 Rxf6 47. e4 $18 {[%cal Gf5e4,
Gf3e4,Gh4f5]}) 42... Nxg6 43. Rxg6 Ref7 44. Re1 Re7 {And White cannot break e4.
} 45. Reg1 Ref7 46. Rxf6 Rxf6 47. e4 fxe4+ 48. Kxe4 Kf7 49. Kf3 Kf8 50. Re1 Kf7
51. Kg4 Kf8 52. Re6 Kf7 53. f5 Kf8 54. Rxf6+ 1/2-1/2

