{[%evp 0,103,16,-16,-20,-45,25,-31,-10,-45,-48,-34,-21,-24,-12,-6,16,23,57,38,
26,-10,11,-4,-4,1,-2,-24,-24,-24,-15,-15,-25,-16,-23,-33,-18,-21,-5,-34,2,1,15,
-10,12,-6,41,20,14,-5,-6,-34,72,-34,-34,-37,62,-37,35,-14,11,12,-167,-89,12,12,
51,-63,-31,-368,-229,-229,-307,-311,-129,-207,-207,-185,-135,-131,0,-131,4,4,
87,82,215,153,153,147,53,53,53,78,308,379,412,412,412,412,412,473,481,481,461,
490]} 1. b3 Nf6 2. Bb2 g6 3. c4 {The game follows our repertoire, even tho 3.
Bxf6 is also a very interesting way to continue, and I have a very good score
in an online blitz in this line.} Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 c5 6. Nf3 d6 7. d4 {
Now it is the time to strike, as otherwise ...e5 is coming with a double-edged,
but fine position for Black overall.} Nc6 8. d5 Na5 {The Panno setup is not
the best system to counter the double fianchetto in this position.} 9. Nfd2 {
A bit unnecessary, as Nbd2 was also perfectly fine.} (9. Nbd2 a6 10. O-O b5 11.
e4 {And the c4 is anyways well protected.}) 9... a6 10. a4 {A new way of
playing, as usually games would continue with Nc3,0-0 and a more standard way.
This move has the intention to stop b5, and also open the a-file for the rook.}
e6 11. Na3 {Designed to make use of the c4 square.} exd5 12. cxd5 Bd7 13. Ra2 {
Vey nice move, defending the bishop and also freeing the a1 square for the
queen in some cases.} b5 14. O-O bxa4 (14... Rb8 15. axb5 axb5 16. Qa1 $1 {
A well-known Reti systems idea.}) 15. bxa4 Rb8 16. Bc3 {Standard move to put
pressure on the knight.} Ng4 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Qa1+ $1 {Correctly assessing
that the endgame is pretty dubious for Black} Nf6 (18... Qf6 $6 19. Nac4 $1
Qxa1 20. Rfxa1 Nxc4 21. Nxc4 $14) 19. Rb1 {Trading blacks most active piece.} (
19. Qc3 {maybe stronger}) 19... Rxb1+ 20. Naxb1 Kg8 21. e4 {Premature decision.
} (21. h3 {Better, prophylaxis against any Ng4}) 21... Ng4 $1 {Correctly using
the square.} 22. Qc3 f5 23. h3 Nf6 24. exf5 Bxf5 {Now Blacks pieces are very
much alive.} 25. Rb2 {Just a waste of time.} (25. Na3 {Was better to directly
start improving the knight.}) 25... Nd7 $2 {Logical move, but missed on a
strong opportunity to equalize.} (25... Qe8 $1 {Very strong resource.} 26. Qxa5
Qe1+ $1 27. Kh2 (27. Bf1 Bd3 28. Qc3 Ne4 $19) 27... Bxh3 $3 {Incredible
tactics, the game ends in a perpetual.} 28. Kxh3 Ng4 $1 29. f4 $1 (29. Kxg4 $4
Qe5 {mate is unstopable}) 29... Nf2+ 30. Kh2 Ng4+ 31. Kh3 $11) 26. Bf1 $6 {
Inaccuracy, as black gets a strong push.} (26. g4 $1 {Best move, giving up the
Black squares is justified.} Bxb1 27. Rxb1 Ne5 28. Ne4 $16 {And white gains a
lot of momentum, due to ideas of Re1 or g5.}) 26... Nf6 $6 {In time trouble
Black repeated.} (26... c4 $1 27. Nxc4 Nxc4 28. Qxc4 Ne5 29. Qc3 Qd7 {And
black gets some initiative.}) 27. Bg2 Nd7 28. Na3 {Better choice than Bf1.} Ne5
29. Bf1 $6 {Now white missed Blacks strong resource.} (29. Ne4 {was a
necessary move now to stop ideas related to Qf6, and the arising positions are
complex, leading to an objective slight advantage for White.}) 29... Qf6 $1 {
is Very nice find by Sabino, sacrificing the knight for a lot of initiative
against the White king.} 30. Qxa5 {White captured the piece because the
opponent was low on time, but it's objectively losing now.} (30. Ndc4 {The
only move to hold balance.} Naxc4 31. Nxc4 Bxh3 32. Nxe5 Bxf1 33. Kxf1 Qxe5 $11
) 30... Bxh3 $1 {Blacks point of the last move.} 31. f4 Ng4 $2 {The most
natural.} (31... Bxf1 $1 {The tough to find a win.} 32. Kxf1 Nd3 $1 (32... Ng4
$2 33. Ndc4 $1 {Holds for White.}) 33. Rc2 Qe5 $1 {Beautiful geometry.} 34. Nf3
Qh5 $1 35. Kg2 Qg4 {And now White is hopeless, because Nf4 is unstoppable.})
32. Bxh3 Qd4+ 33. Kh1 Qxd5+ 34. Bg2 $2 {Objectively bad move, but White is
playing on time now.} (34. Kg1 Qd4+ $11) 34... Qh5+ $1 35. Kg1 Qh2+ 36. Kf1
Qxg3 $2 {The most natural move is a mistake.} (36... Ne3+ $1 37. Ke2 Re8 {
The winning idea.} 38. Kd3 Qxg2 $19) 37. Bd5+ (37. Nf3 {was stronger} Ne3+ 38.
Kg1 Nxg2 39. Rxg2 Qxf3 $13) 37... Kh8 38. Ke2 Qe3+ 39. Kd1 Qxa3 (39... Qg1+ {
The best way to play.} 40. Ke2 Qf2+ 41. Kd3 Qd4+ 42. Kc2 Ne3+ $13 {Very
unclear position, but probably better for Black.}) 40. Kc1 (40. Rb3 $13) 40...
Qe3 (40... Nf2 $1 {The last move to try and claim advantage for Black.}) 41.
Rb3 Qe1+ {Inaccurate, on g1 was better, but the position is already unpleasant
to play with Black.} 42. Kb2 Rxf4 43. Qd8+ Kg7 44. Nf3 Qe2+ 45. Ka3 {Finally
our king is safe.} Nf6 46. Ng5 Kh6 $2 (46... Rxa4+ {The last chance to hope to
save the game for Black.} 47. Kxa4 Qa2+ 48. Ra3 Qxd5 49. Qe7+ Kg8 50. Qe6+ Qxe6
51. Nxe6 Kf7 {And the arising endgame is evaluated as only +2, so still white
has to prove the win.}) 47. Nf7+ $1 {And now Black is lost} Kh5 48. Rh3+ Kg4
49. Qc8+ $1 Rf5 50. Bf3+ Qxf3+ 51. Rxf3 Kxf3 52. Nxd6 {A very adventurous game!
} 1-0

