{[%evp 0,83,19,-31,35,15,16,-17,-13,-35,-18,-22,-7,-26,5,-3,7,-25,22,24,70,70,
82,83,93,87,108,108,109,66,66,96,96,109,123,0,0,0,-21,-50,-11,-2,-2,-3,-3,0,0,
8,3,-1,25,0,27,27,50,63,39,64,93,18,88,121,143,121,163,116,216,44,228,223,234,
239,432,471,524,540,587,587,700,708,818,840,29993,29994,29995,29996]} 1. b3 g6
2. Bb2 Nf6 3. c4 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 {Black chose to play in more of a
king's Indian setup spirit.} 6. d4 e5 7. dxe5 Nfd7 {This is a position that we
also check in the theory part of the course.} 8. Nc3 dxe5 9. Qd2 {We don't
play moves like Nf3 and 0-0 because we try to anticipate the ...c6 move from
Black, and also Nf3 closes the g2 monster.} c6 (9... Nc5 {Best way to play} 10.
Qe3 Nbd7 {And we reach a complex position that is analyzed more profoundly in
the theory part.}) 10. Ba3 $1 {All suddenly, White is creating concrete
problems for Black.} Re8 11. Ne4 {And Blacks pieces are kind of stuck and in
each others way.} a5 {With the idea to reroute the knight to b4 and shut down
the strong a3 bishop.} 12. Nf3 {Now we can safely develop, as c6 is already
played.} Na6 13. Rd1 {Strong move, as we are in no hurry to castle, we could
use some h4-h5 ideas also.} Nb4 {Black executes his idea.} 14. O-O Qe7 15. Nd6
Rd8 16. Bh3 $1 {Very strong find; in any case, we don't allow the knight from
d7 to move, so Black's Kingside remains stuck for longer.} f5 {More human way
of playing.} (16... Nc5 17. Bxc8 Qc7 {Tough move to spot.} (17... Bf8 $2 18.
Nf5 $1 $18 {The bishop on c8 disrupts the rooks protection.}) 18. Bxb4 axb4 19.
Qxb4 b6 20. Nb7 Nxb7 21. Bxb7 Qxb7 {After finding all this from Black, still
White is for choice, who is up a pawn for little compensation.}) 17. Bxf5 $1 {
The most logical continuation, it's not forced by any means, e4 is also good,
but the position of black pieces is so uncomfortable that sacrificing the
piece is a natural way of proceeding in this case.} gxf5 18. Nxf5 {The
compensation is clearly visible, we sacrificed with tempo, collected two pawns
and will eliminate the important g7 bishop, and our bishop from a3 will go to
b2 and enjoy amazing prospects on the long a1-h8 diagonal. Black still has to
find a decent way to unpin his pieces.} Qf6 19. Nxg7 Qxg7 20. Bb2 {Engines
confirm this position White had in mind, and the human evaluation: 17.Bxf5 was
objectively the best way to continue.} Re8 21. a3 Na6 22. Qxa5 {We collect
another pawn.} b6 23. Qd2 Nac5 24. b4 Ne4 25. Qe3 Nef6 (25... Ndf6 {Engine
suggests to give out the pawn at least for some activity} 26. Qxb6 Bh3 27. Rfe1
Ng4) 26. Rd6 $1 {Our pieces are fully mobilized.} c5 27. Rfd1 {Last piece to
join.} Ra7 28. h3 $1 {First line of engine, to limit any Ng4.} Qe7 29. g4 {
We control the f5 square and introduce some Nh4-f5 ideas.} Rc7 30. b5 $1 {
Important touch to crump Black position and not allow any counterplay.} Qg7 31.
Ng5 Ra7 32. f3 Kh8 33. h4 {Now Black shuold just wait with Kg8, but the
position is very bad anyway.} Qg8 $2 {Final mistake.} 34. Rxf6 $1 Nxf6 35. Bxe5
Qf8 36. Bxf6+ Kg8 37. Ne4 {And the rest is smooth sailing for White.} h6 38.
Bb2 Rae7 39. Qc3 Re5 40. Rd5 Rxd5 41. Qh8+ Kf7 42. Qf6+ 1-0

