{[#]} 8. a4 $1 {a4! It's a move we will play only now. Why? Let's follow the
logic: a4 weakens the b4 square, which could allow Black to capitalize by
playing a7-a5 and Na6-Nb4. However, since Black has already developed the
knight to d7, exploiting the b4 square becomes less feasible. But what are the
benefits of playing a4? Generally, White aims to seize space on the queenside,
with the potential for moves like Ba3. However, the most crucial aspect is
preventing Black from playing b7-b5. In fact, if White starts with 8.d4, Black
has the strong response 8...b5!. So 8.a4 is also preventing Black from playing
b7-b5} (8. d4 b5 $1 $11) 8... a5 (8... Re8 9. d4 Ne4 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Nf6
12. Ne5 $14) 9. d4 {Since we've stopped Black from playing b7-b5, thanks to
the inclusion of a4-a5, it's time for our next move: d2-d4. It's pretty
straightforward: Black wants to play e7-e5, so we block that with d2-d4} Ne4
10. Nbd2 {White is typically slightly better in these positions} *

